ncluding immunoglobulins"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe liver \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduces most plasma proteins except immunoglobulins\u003C/strong\u003E, which are synthesised by plasma cells. The liver is responsible for synthesising important proteins including albumin, most clotting factors, and acute phase proteins. However, some proteins like immunoglobulins and von Willebrand factor are produced elsewhere.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynthesises all plasma proteins including immunoglobulins\u003C/strong\u003E - Immunoglobulins are produced by plasma cells, not the liver\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynthesises proteins only during feeding states\u003C/strong\u003E - Protein synthesis occurs continuously, not just during feeding\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStores but does not synthesise plasma proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - The liver actively synthesises rather than just stores proteins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcesses proteins only during fasting states\u003C/strong\u003E - Protein processing occurs continuously, not just during fasting\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe liver receives amino acids from the portal circulation and uses them to synthesise most plasma proteins through transcription and translation. This is a continuous process essential for maintaining normal plasma protein levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The liver synthesizes most plasma proteins except immunoglobulins and von Willebrand factor.","Albumin is the most abundant plasma protein and is exclusively produced by the liver.","The liver processes dietary amino acids into plasma proteins through transcription and translation."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy 